</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CC8514CE6CB1FCAF6D53CAB01E1B998F" pageId="780" pageNumber="781">
<taxonomicName id="42BE88F0AF4A416AC824DBDD9BDA96F6" authorityName="Motschulsky" authorityYear="1862" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Polyderis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="780" pageNumber="781" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="glabrella">Polyderis glabrella</taxonomicName>
Motschulsky, 1862b: 34. Type locality: &quot;Mobile [Mobile County, Alabama]&quot; (original citation). Lectotype, designated by Erwin (1974a: 127), in ZMMU. Synonymy established by Erwin (1974a: 127).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="ECA9A2D27A9BBE2666229B1046FFCCBB" pageId="780" pageNumber="781" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="717E80879349EAEF20EB3414E22E5247" pageId="780" pageNumber="781">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="16364364D4159830B24AE79FEBDDBB05" pageId="780" pageNumber="781">
This species is subcosmopolitan. It is adventive in North America where it is known from Nova Scotia (Pictou County, CNC) to eastern Iowa (Muscatine County, Doug A. Veal pers. comm. 2009), south to east-central Texas (Riley 2011), central Louisiana (Grant Parish, CNC) and southern Florida (Peck and Thomas 1998: 23) in the east, and from Oregon (Hatch 1953: 147) to southern California (Fall 1901a: 47) in the west. The first inventoried specimen collected on this continent was found prior to 1853 (LeConte 1853c: 386, as 
<taxonomicName id="3790735FEB2F44AEC95097833D7EF27F" authorityName="LeConte" authorityYear="1853" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Trechicus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="780" pageNumber="781" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="umbripennis">
<emphasis id="1E2024606EFBFBCCE5C0E37FEFA64227" italics="true" pageId="780" pageNumber="781">Trechicus umbripennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Basilewsky (1953a: 108) believed the species originated along the coast of the Indian Ocean where it is very abundant in rubbish and groundnut.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="3D0EC5F40AB33555FB264A67DBC97AA0" pageId="780" pageNumber="781" type="records">
<paragraph id="6FC6E15C9892FF5091E02D0883696AD0" pageId="780" pageNumber="781">Records.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7417DAC87EF13AAB4598CDAE771F0F78" pageId="780" pageNumber="781">
<emphasis id="C58780376A905DC36FFD983D11EBF80C" bold="true" pageId="780" pageNumber="781">CAN</emphasis>
: NB, NS, ON, QC 
<emphasis id="0B805B6AAF648AFA32000382FA4A7FB3" bold="true" pageId="780" pageNumber="781">USA</emphasis>
: AL, AR, CA, CT, DC, FL, GA, IA, IL, IN, KY, LA, MA, MD, ME, MI, MS, NC, NE, NH, NJ, NY, OH, OR, PA, RI, SC, TX, VA, VT, WI, WV - 
<emphasis id="B48F87C8185BE3438E01270402745A17" bold="true" pageId="780" pageNumber="781">Adventive</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<caption id="3A9E58D76A5ACC75995CD7960F6435A2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/30939" pageId="780" pageNumber="781" start="Figure 38" startId="F38">
<paragraph id="82162327CA90CD8E8D73B806DFF93C22" pageId="780" pageNumber="781">
<emphasis id="8D45E5713F198CBF0535AEEF6AC53607" bold="true" pageId="780" pageNumber="781">Figure 38.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="8E368DFFD7B2BCA9E7F9471A97F0A2D2" baseAuthorityName="Dejean" baseAuthorityYear="1831" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Perigona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="780" pageNumber="781" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigriceps">
<emphasis id="4CEF793528A5D09C6C109277343A83BC" italics="true" pageId="780" pageNumber="781">Perigona nigriceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Dejean). While most adventive carabid species have been introduced from Europe, this species, which is now subcosmopolitan, is probably native from southern Asia where it is common around the Indian Ocean. Contrary to European adventive species which have been introduced to North America through ballast and nursery stocks, this species was probably transported around the world among stored products on ships.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
